'''Keith Collar Clark''' (November 21, 1927 – January 10, 2002)<ref name=TB-Clark>{{cite web |url=http://tapsbugler.com/keith-clark-bugler-at-jfks-funeral/ |title=Keith Clark, Bugler at JFK’s Funeral |publisher=Taps Bugler |accessdate=18 December 2014 }}</ref> was a [[bugler]] in the [[United States Army]] who played the call "[[Taps]]" at the [[state funeral of John F. Kennedy|funeral]] of President [[John F. Kennedy]] in 1963. He fluffed the sixth note, and to many this mistake was a poignant symbol of the American nation in mourning.<ref name=TB-Taps>{{cite web |url=http://tapsbugler.com/a-bugle-call-remembered/ |title=A Bugle Call Remembered - Taps at the funeral of President John F. Kennedy |publisher=Taps Bugler |accessdate=18 December 2014 }}</ref> The bugle that Clark used is on display at the welcome center of Arlington National Cemetery.
== Career == As lead bugler of the [[United States Army Band]] when Kennedy was assassinated, Clark was assigned the task of playing ''Taps'' at the president's funeral.<ref name="AP news">{{Cite news |url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1988/Bugler-Recalls-Missing-Note-While-Playing-Taps-At-Kennedy-Funeral/id-8c09991db50bc5b40e7665dc06af5aba |title=Bugler Recalls Missing Note While Playing Taps At Kennedy Funeral |date=1998-11-14 |access-date=2017-07-14 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> On the day of the funeral, Clark stood in the rain for three hours before it was time for him to play.<ref name="NY Times">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/17/us/keith-clark-bugler-for-kennedy-dies-at-74.html |title=Keith Clark, Bugler for Kennedy, Dies at 74 |last=Goldstein |first=Richard |date=2002-01-17 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2017-07-14 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> At 3:08 PM, after the 21 gun salute, Clark started to play ''Taps'', and fluffed the sixth note.<ref name="AP news" /><ref name="JFK library">{{Cite news |url=https://www.jfklibrary.org/Research/Research-Aids/Ready-Reference/JFK-Fast-Facts/Funeral-Music.aspx |title=Accurate Listing of Funeral Music |last=Lowens |first=Irving |date=1963-12-01 |work=Washington Star |accessdate=2017-07-14}}</ref>
After the funeral, many assumed the mistake was intentional.<ref name="AP news" /><ref name="NY Times" />
